The music video theme compresses all the essences of my emotional experiences that I have felt during the whole trip. During the whole trip, I have been to Mt. Fuji , Meiji Shrine, Hirajuku streets and many others. All those places were worthy to visit and nice but I couldnâ€™t get rid of feeling that the places seem to be a bit old and rusty, dull. After watching the music video, I thought to myself that Japan is a beautiful country , in reality the nation itself is an aged nation going through the transitional time where the nation is moving away from its past golden age.

This reminds me, that my Grandfather, who was my Grandmother's third husband (Gary Ulrich) had been a 'Hells Angel' member in the 1960s. He told me what the initiation evolved, and how he was 'Jumped in', much of what was involved, was gross.  Then, I found out that he had also been, a member of the Roller Derby  in the 50s and 60s.  His position was as a 'Jammer' who was an 'Enforcer' who would provoke the other team to fight. Grandma and he divorced in the mid 1970s. I did see Gary  in the early 1980s, when our Aunty Cille died, and I couldn't believe what I saw; it was Gary, but now he was working as a Private Investigator.  He was dressed in an all white three piece suit. He was driving Grandma's 1959 Cadillac convertible, it was 'Triple white', and showed me the two pearl handled 45s he wore, concealed under his blazer in crossed shoulder holsters. He had the same haircut he always had; his natural hair color was white, it was naturally peroxide blonde. And it was styled in the 'Jellyroll DA' swept back on the sides, and curly on top. He used Pomade; alot of it. When I saw him, he went to great lengths to give me his business card, and show me his guns. He looked like a man, out of his time, trying to hold on to his 'High Times' of the past. I wish I had a camera, to record the spectacle. He also had a white mustache, that extended, down on the sides of his mouth. His cheeks were concave, he had always been, a thin, angry man. But fun to be with, because, you always felt like, you were, getting away with something, some kind of illegal activity.  What a guy!  I never knew, how he may have died, but I bet it was in a shootout or something terrible. I'd pour a beer out over your grave, if I knew where it was. â¤

The saddest part about this song is that this happens to all of us. Someday teens like me will be old like those grandparents, reminescing on the good old days while new teens enjoy their youth. I already feel some of my youth slipping away. And after living out my life, I won't have anything else to do for all eternity

Also the happiest part. Getting to reminisce about the good times you've had together. There is joy in watching younger folks discover life, solve problems and create their own paths. Responsibilities & problems have a way of weighing us down, chipping away at our youthful nature, sucking the fun out of life, and stress tends to accelerate our aging. It does get better and we have to remember that we're all strapped into this rollercoaster of ups, downs, twists & loops, so just lift your arms and say woo-hoo as we ride! Mental age is mostly a number as we don't really feel that different as we age even when our bodies do. Good luck and many blessings to you and those that read this.

Think they refer to it as a "manji" and it means something completely different to them that it does to the west. For them, they did not let the symbol become twisted into the nazi ideals and connotations, since it has a very long history as a symbol of divinity and spirituality in Buddism. An example would be if instead of the swastika, nazi Germany used a cross. All Catholics and Christians and believers of Jesus Christ would not let that taint the original meaning and symbolism of the cross. Buddhism just isn't popular in the west.
